Data Cleaning

Data cleaning is one of the biggest challenges in Machine Learning when it comes to use data. It is very critical for the success of ML applications. Even though with a powerful algorithm, ideal results are not secure without the relevant ot right training data. In order to improve the quality of the training data for analytics and enables accurate decision-making we will use Data cleaning that will identify and remove errors and duplicate data.

Data cleaning consists on:

  1. Fill-out missing values
  2. Removing rows with missing values
  3. Fixing errors in the structure
  4. Reducing data for proper data handling

Data Understanding and Visualizing

We will start with univariate analysis which is the simplest form of data analysis. Since it's a single variable it doesn’t deal with causes or relationships.

In [10]:
# Get  columns whose data type is int 
filteredColumns = df.dtypes[df.dtypes == np.int64]
listOfColumnNames = list(filteredColumns.index)

for i  in listOfColumnNames:
    if len(df[i].unique()) >  10 :

      plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
      sns.distplot(df.loc[:, i], kde=True , color = 'orange')
      plt.title(r'$\bf{%s}$ distribution with median of %.2f and mean of %.2f' % \
              (i, np.median(df.loc[:, i]), df.loc[:, i].mean()),
              size=14)
      plt.xlabel(i, fontsize=15)
      plt.xticks(fontsize=15)
      plt.yticks(fontsize=15)
      plt.axvline(np.median(df.loc[:, i]), 0, linestyle='--',
                linewidth=1.5, color='r')
      plt.show()

There are $1470$ employees and $16 \%$ of them left the company. Half of the workers are below $36$ years old, with an average age of $36.92$. More than $50\%$ the workers live nearby the company, with an average distance of $9.19$ Km. The monthly income spans $1,000 \ \$$ to $20,000 \ \$$. Half of the workers earn less than $5,000 \ \$$, and the rest is spread out more evenely between $5,000 \ \$$ and $20,000 \ \$$. Most of the workers have worked $10$ years or less, with a maximum of $40$ years and a mean of $11.28$. More specifically, most of the workers have worked less than $10$ years at the company, with a median of $5$ years and an average of $7.01$ years. In avergae, workers stay in the same position for $4.23$ years, with $50\%$ of them changing in less than $3$ years.

Comment

Most of the workers graduated with a bachelor's degree. Some hold a master's degree, and very few have a PhD. There is also a group of wokers who haven't attended college nor high school. Most of the workers with an educational background studied life sciences or medicine. We also see that 66% of the wokers are satified with the environment, and a notable 33% aren't. The job stafiaction level is not perfect, 33% aren't satisfied. Despite the negative feedback, most of them are well involved. The job roles with highest number of positions are Sales Executive, Laboratory Technician, and Research Scientist. A small but noticebale amount of workers work overtime. Saying this, most workers have a decent work life balance, while a few are struglling to find a balance. Regarding their social satuses, around half are single while the other half is shared by married and divorced workers. On a final note, there are more males than females in the company.

Multivariable Analysis

Multivariate analysis is concerned with the interrelationships among several variables. This kind of analysis is more interesting as it illustrates the relationships among the various characteristics. The aim of the project is to predict employee attrition that is why we will be using multivariable analysis to understand the influence of the various factors on the predicted variable.

Now we will try to understand why employees are leaving the company.

In [12]:
df2 = df.copy()
df2['Attrition'] = df2['Attrition'].apply(lambda x: 0 if x == 'No' else 1)
In [13]:
def graph_df(x, y = 'bar', z = 0):
    feature = df2.groupby(x).agg({'Attrition':['size', 'sum', 'mean']})
    feature.columns = [' '.join(col).strip() for col in feature.columns.values]
    feature = feature.reset_index()
    feature['Attrition mean'] = feature['Attrition mean']*100
    feature.columns = [x, 'Total Employee', 'Attrition Number', '% of Attrition in the Relevant Group']
    feature['% of Attrition in the Company'] = (feature['Attrition Number'] / 237) * 100

    fig, ax1 = plt.subplots()
    ax2 = ax1.twinx()
    feature.set_index(feature[x], drop=True, inplace=True)
    feature['Total Employee'].plot(kind = y, stacked = True, ax = ax1, colormap = 'summer', rot = z)
    feature['% of Attrition in the Relevant Group'].plot(use_index = False, kind = 'line', ax = ax2, colormap='Spectral')
    plt.title('Attrition compared to ' + x  + ' Groups', size=16)
    ax1.set_xlabel(x, size=14)
    ax1.yaxis.label.set_color('blue')
    ax1.set_ylabel("Total Employee", size=14)
    ax2.set_ylabel("Attrition Percentage in the Relevant Group", size=14)
    ax2.yaxis.label.set_color('red')
    zoom = 1.5
    w, h = fig.get_size_inches()
    fig.set_size_inches(w * zoom, h * zoom)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    return feature

Scoring Function¶

In [62]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report, confusion_matrix

def print_score(clf, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, train=True):

    if train:
        pred = clf.predict(X_train)
        print("Training Result:\n")
        print("Accuracy: {0:.4f}\n".format(accuracy_score(y_train, pred)))
        print("Confusion Matrix: \n {}".format(confusion_matrix(y_train, pred)))

    else:
        pred = clf.predict(X_test)
        print("Testing Result:\n")
        print("Accuracy score: {0:.4f}\n".format(accuracy_score(y_test, pred)))
        print("Confusion Matrix: \n {}".format(confusion_matrix(y_test, pred)))
